    <h1>The Great Sin&#xAD;ga&#xAD;pore Drive</h1>
    <h2>Who says Sin&#xAD;ga&#xAD;pore is too small for a good road trip? Fol&#xAD;low Straits Times as&#xAD;sis&#xAD;tant news ed&#xAD;i&#xAD;tor Toh Yong Chuan on a 200km drive around the is&#xAD;land to dis&#xAD;cover lit&#xAD;tle-known spots and spe&#xAD;cial look&#xAD;out points.</h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201031/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-10-31"><time>2020-10-31</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE MOTORING</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>8 Old Up­per Thomson Road Grand Prix cir­cuit 1961-1973</p>
    <p>• Be­tween 1961 and 1973, this was the street cir­cuit for the Malaysian Grand Prix and Sin­ga­pore Grand Prix.</p>
    <p>• The 4.8km cir­cuit has catchy names like Thomson Mile and Devil’s Bend.</p>
    <p>• A 3km stretch is now a one-way street to ac­com­mo­date a park con­nec­tor.</p>
    <p>9 Ca­sua­r­ina tree at Up­per Sele­tar Reser­voir</p>
    <p>• This lone ca­sua­r­ina tree at Up­per Sele­tar Reser­voir is one of Sin­ga­pore’s most iconic trees. It is flanked by benches and is a favourite spot for bridal pho­tog­ra­phy. 7 Ri­fle Range Road</p>
    <p>• The lit­tle-known stretch off Dun­earn Road cuts into the Bukit Timah Na­ture Re­serve. 10 Soek Seng 1954 Bi­cy­cle Cafe • Din­ers can en­joy views of the Sele­tar Air­port run­way and parked planes from the eatery.</p>
    <p>• Opened in 2016, the cafe is named af­ter the mo­tor work­shop set up in 1954 by the owner ’s fa­ther.</p>


